Part 1. Course Design Principles
Coursera follows three fundamental principles that work together to create modular, skill-aligned learning experiences:

Skill-First Learning: Each course is aligned to specific skills or skill areas
 ⇨ Content specifications will define the skill focus


Standalone & Stackable Courses: Every element works independently and in combination
 ⇨ No dependencies, unlimited reusability


WWHAA Design Footprint: Use this design pattern for every module
 ⇨ Consistent, effective learning through Why-What-How-Apply-Assess design pattern

These principles work together: You'll create skill-first courses that are standalone and stackable, using the WWHAA footprint for each module. 
Principle #1 - Skill-First Learning
Your primary objective is to enable and validate skill mastery. 
Verified Assessments
Verified Assessments are rigorous evaluations in the Skill Mastery framework that provide evidence of a learner's ability to perform skills in practice. These assessments fully and accurately measure Skill Expressions by covering their intended scope and evaluating performance at the appropriate Bloom's level (e.g., Apply, Analyze, Evaluate, Create).

Understanding that learners will be working toward passing a Verified Assessment helps you design course content and assessments that align with this standard of skill demonstration, ensuring learners develop the practical competencies needed for authentic workplace application.
Assessment Design Principles
Verified Assessments are grounded in authentic, workplace-relevant scenarios and project-based tasks that mirror actual professional challenges. Rather than decontextualized exams, these assessments present learners with complex, realistic situations that require them to demonstrate real-world skill application.
Skill Expression Coverage
Each Skill Expression must be assessed at least once within the Verified Assessment framework. Assessment questions are designed flexibly; e.g., a single scenario-based question can evaluate multiple Skill Expressions simultaneously, while individual Skill Expressions may be assessed through multiple questions when comprehensive validation is needed. This approach ensures thorough coverage while maintaining authentic, job-relevant assessment experiences.
Alignment to Learning Levels
All assessment items must align to appropriate Bloom's taxonomy levels that match the cognitive complexity of the target Skill Expressions. Assessments focus on higher-order thinking skills (Apply, Analyze, Evaluate, Create) that reflect real workplace demands rather than lower-level recall or comprehension.
Skill Areas
Each long course is centered on a Skill Area. A Skill Area is a learner-facing grouping of related skills that support a common phase of work or functional objective. The skills in a Skill Area are commonly taught, practiced, or applied together. Skill Areas support navigation, credential design, and curriculum bundling, without defining structural or prerequisite relationships.
Skills
Each module within a short or long course addresses one Skill. Skills are learned competencies — specific knowledge, techniques, or abilities that can be developed through practice, training, or experience.
Skill Expressions
Each skill is associated with one or more Skill Expression. A Skill Expression is a discrete, observable, and measurable capability that enables a person to perform a specific task or function. Skill Expressions are the building blocks of our Skill Mastery measurement system. 
Skill Expressions & Learning Objectives
When designing your course, Skill Expressions serve as the foundation for your learning objectives. In some cases, a Skill Expression may directly become a learning objective. However, complex Skill Expressions often need to be broken down into multiple, more specific learning objectives that scaffold learners toward mastery. 

For example, a Skill Expression such as “Apply visual design principles to enhance clarity, impact, and narrative in visualizations” might translate into separate learning objectives covering color theory, typography, layout principles, and storytelling techniques. Your role is to determine the appropriate level of granularity that supports effective learning while ensuring all aspects of the Skill Expression are addressed.
Structuring the Learning Experience
Here is how the Skill Mastery framework maps onto Coursera platform structures:

Long Course (multiple modules) ⇨ Skill Area
Short Course (typically one to three modules) ⇨ Skill
Module ⇨ Skill
Items ⇨ Skill Expression(s)

Short Courses are designed around a specific Skill and typically consist of one focused module. When there are multiple Skill Expressions or Skills that require more comprehensive treatment, short courses may include additional modules.

Long Courses are designed around a specific Skill Area and consist of multiple modules where each module addresses a skill. 
