Principle #2 - Standalone & Stackable Courses
All courses need to provide self-contained, standalone learning experiences that can function independently while also combining seamlessly into larger learning pathways. Each short course is a complete, valuable learning experience on its own.
Standalone Design Principles
Every element of your course—from individual items to complete modules—must be self-contained so that it makes sense on its own.

This also allows the content to be reordered, extracted, and used across multiple courses and programs. Because a single module may appear in more than one course or a single course may appear in more than one Specialization or Professional Certificate, authors should frame content so that it makes sense in different program contexts.

Do not reference other parts of the course, sequences of courses, or programs the course may be part of. Do include any necessary context within each item.

Here are some examples:



❌Don’t Say
✅ Do Say
Module Transitions
“Now that you’ve mastered the basics from Module 1, let’s apply those concepts to…”
“Data transformation is essential for analysis. Let’s explore how to use SQL functions to…”


“Building on our previous discussion about variables…”
“Variables store data values. Let’s see how to use them in functions…”
Course/Program References
“As part of this Data Science Specialization, you’ll use these skills in the capstone project…”
“These data preprocessing skills are essential for any machine learning project. Let’s practice with a real dataset…”


“This builds on the Python Basics course you completed earlier…”
“Using Python’s data structures, we can efficiently process large datasets…”
Stackability Across Programs
“This course is your first step in the Data Analyst Specialization.”
“These foundational data analysis skills are relevant across a variety of career paths.”
Sequential References
“In the previous lesson, we explored how to optimize this code…”
“Code optimization involves several key strategies…”


“In the next video, we’ll dive deeper into this topic…”
“As a next step, try the advanced features of this tool…”


“By now, you should have completed the three exercises from earlier…”
“Let’s practice with a hands-on exercise that demonstrates these concepts…”
Assessment References
“Remember this for the final quiz…”
“This concept is fundamental to understanding how databases work…”


“You’ll need this for your capstone project…”
“This skill has immediate application in real-world projects…”


“This extends what you learned in Assignment 1…”
“Let’s apply data validation techniques to ensure accuracy…”
Video/Reading Transitions
“As I mentioned in the previous video…”
“An important consideration when designing APIs is…”


“The reading you just completed explained…”
“RESTful APIs follow specific architectural principles. Let’s implement them…”


“Before watching the next video, make sure you understand…”
“Let’s ensure we have a solid grasp of these core concepts…”

Stackable Design Benefits
When courses are truly standalone, they become infinitely stackable:

Same course can appear in multiple learning paths
Modules can be reordered or extracted based on learner needs
Content remains relevant regardless of learning path
Updates to one course don't break dependencies
Principle #3 - The WWHAA Design Footprint
Every instructional module in a Coursera course should follow the WWHAA design footprint, a design framework that structures content delivery through five distinct phases: Why, What, How, Apply, and Assess.
Modules as the Building Blocks of Learning
For those who have worked with Coursera in the past, we've simplified our course architecture so that a module acts as the fundamental container of content within a course; there are no longer separate “lesson” containers within a module.
Old Structure:
Courses contained Modules
Modules contained Lessons
Lessons contained individual learning items
New Structure:
Courses contain Modules
Modules contain all learning items
No separate "lesson" container will be used
Modules are the “lessons” within a short course

Each module addresses one Skill, composed of one or more Skill Expressions. In long courses, multiple modules collectively cover all skills within a Skill Area. In short courses, typically one module addresses the targeted Skill Expression(s) directly. When the topic requires more comprehensive treatment, short courses may include additional modules while maintaining their targeted scope.
Working with Module Specifications & Course Structure
Your Role: Design effective learning experiences using the WWHAA footprint for each module.

You will receive information that includes:
Course format (long or short course)
Module titles
Occupation group (professional role for target audience)
Skill to address within each module
Skill expressions to cover in the learning items
Skill expression descriptions for more context
Job tasks (ideas for activities)

Job Tasks: Job tasks should be taken as illustrative examples. The learning designer and subject matter expert (SME) have latitude to identify and develop the most relevant activities to teach the skills. When developing scenarios, examples, or activities, design them for professionals in the specified Occupation Group — this is your target learner audience.

Tool Selection: Unless the skill expression or title explicitly mentions a specific tool, you have latitude to develop a manageable set of tools/projects. Consider all courses in the program together and select the most appropriate and relevant set of tools/languages, keeping in mind industry-standard tools and a manageable number of tools for the learner.

Long Courses (Skill Area-based): You'll implement multiple modules that work together to cover a comprehensive Skill Area. Each module addresses specific Skills within that broader area.

Short Courses (Skill-based): You'll typically implement one focused module, though some assignments may include additional modules when skill complexity requires it.
Overview of WWHAA Design Footprint
The WWHAA design footprint applies to each module in the course. 

Phase
Purpose & Design Guidance
Recommended Item Types
Why
Purpose: Help learners understand why the content matters to their careers and real-world applications.

Design Guidance:
• Feature human SMEs explaining skill value from industry experience
• Use real-world examples with learner-centric framing
• Hook learners through storytelling and job alignment
 Dialogue 
• Establish the personal value of the topic to the learner

Video
• Instructor-led talking head or voice-over slides

Reading
• Career-relevant information connecting to professional growth
What
Purpose: Introduce key ideas, terminology, and foundational concepts. This is the core instructional moment focusing on declarative knowledge.

Design Guidance:
• Include one or more short video and/or reading
• Vary item types to avoid repetition (e.g., video + reading + video, instead of video + video + video)
• Prioritize clarity, pacing, and early value delivery
 Video 
• Screencast walkthroughs
• Instructional videos

Reading
• With examples, graphics, or code blocks

Ungraded Lab
• Ungraded for conceptual demonstration

Podcast
• Optional podcast/audio summary
How
Purpose: Bridge theory and practice through guided real-world exploration.

Design Guidance:
• Scaffold application in tool-based or scenario-driven contexts
• Support multimodal instruction (visual, auditory, interactive)
 Video
• Demonstration or follow-along tutorials

Reading
• Interactive prompts or walkthroughs

Ungraded Lab 
• Ungraded step-by-step exploration of code environments

Other possibilities:
• Podcast
• Dialogue
Apply
Purpose: Enable learners to use skills in real-world scenarios with decreasing support.

Design Guidance:
• Start with scaffolded items, transition to open-ended practice
• Emphasize job relevance and real-world transfer
• Include "do it yourself" moments reflecting workplace tasks
 Dialogue 
• Learner works through application in interactive dialogue

Practice Assignment 
• Instructions for off-platform hands-on activity with AI graded submissions or reflective responses

Reading 
• Scenario-based readings

Ungraded Lab
• Ungraded labs or practice environments

App Item (LTI) 
• e.g., third-party tool

Ungraded Plugin 
• e.g., interactive
Assess
Purpose: Provide feedback and validate achievement of learning objectives.

Design Guidance:
• Include informal “knowledge checks” with feedback near end of modules
• Include at least one graded assessment per course (end of last module in course)
• Align directly to skill expressions and stated learning objectives
 Practice Assignment
• Auto-graded quiz questions
• AI-graded open-ended questions
• Hands-on activity with AI-graded submission or reflective responses

Graded Assignment
• Auto-graded quiz questions
• AI-graded open-ended questions
• Hands-on activity with AI-graded submission or reflective responses

Programming Assignment 
• Graded Coursera Lab

Peer Review  
• Use AI-graded assignment where possible, reserving peer review assignment for justifiable use cases

Item Sequencing: Mix Deliberately to Maintain Engagement
Item types should be mixed deliberately, avoiding more than two consecutive lectures or readings. Our internal research shows that sequences with varied item types consistently demonstrate higher learner progress and completion rates, while repetitive sequences result in lower engagement and increased drop-off.

Why sequencing matters: Our research reveals that learners drop off at significantly higher rates when encountering repetitive content patterns. Sequences featuring undifferentiated item types (e.g., five consecutive videos or clusters of three videos followed by two readings) create monotonous learning experiences that fail to sustain attention and momentum. Conversely, varied sequences keep learners engaged by alternating between different cognitive demands and modes of interaction, preventing the fatigue that comes from passive consumption of similar content types.

Key principle: No more than two identical item types should appear consecutively. Break up video sequences with readings, practice assessments, or hands-on learning activities to create a dynamic, engaging learning experience that supports sustained progress.
Introducing a Course
Purpose: Motivate learner with real-world value

Design Guidance:
Skip general welcomes (no syllabus reading or course introductory video)
Open with, for example:
Dialogue to assess prior knowledge, explore motivations, set learning goals
"Why" item that establishes real-world value for the topic
Lead with substance that shows immediate career applicability
Move directly toward skill acquisition

Recommended Item Types:
Dialogue - Use to assess prior knowledge or help learner establish personal relevance
Video - SME-led video connecting the skill to industry application
Reading - Scenario-based reading that frames the skill in context of learner goals
Ending a Course
Purpose: Validate achievement of course skill expressions

Design Guidance:
Include course graded assessment at the end of the last module
Exception: If the course involves a more involved hands-on course project with multiple items; then it may warrant its own module

Recommended Item Types: See “Assess” phase above for options
Required Assessments per Course
1+ formative activity (ungraded) per module
1+ knowledge check (ungraded) per module
1+ summative (graded) assessment per course

Remember, use practice activities and knowledge checks to checkpoint distinct skills in each module; and end the course with a graded assessment.
Learner Access to Tools
Learners often require access to software tools or platforms to learn the skills being taught. If a paid license is required, let learners know this in the course description (i.e., on the landing page) and within relevant course items (e.g., items that cover setup of the tool); then you can assume learners will obtain paid access to complete any necessary activities in the course. If open-access tools or free trials are available, let learners know about these options. 
Accessibility
Vendors are accountable to being up-to-date on the latest Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG) and ensuring they’re met when creating content. 

Content Accessibility Checklist (ERC)
Content Accessibility Policy (ERC)
