Part 2. Creating Hands-on Learning Experiences
Leveraging AI for Hands-on Learning & Assessment 
Coursera's AI learning tools enable you to implement the design principles at scale by creating personalized, hands-on learning experiences that provide immediate feedback on authentic practice opportunities and hands-on graded assessments.
Coach Dialogue Items
Purpose: AI-powered Socratic conversations
When to use: Critical thinking, scenario analysis, concept exploration, reflection
Benefits: Personalized instruction, immediate feedback, scalable tutoring
WWHAA integration: Why (motivation), Apply (scenarios, reflection)

Dialogue items are course activities that enable authors to create AI-driven discussions, simulating interactions with a personal tutor. These items lead learners through structured, text-based conversations designed to achieve specific learning objectives.

In a live Dialogue experience, the AI guide (Coursera Coach) helps learners think critically and apply course concepts to real-world situations by asking adaptive, open-ended questions. Dialogues are tailored to each learner, providing personalized feedback that drives progress and deepens understanding.

For more details on using and setting up Coach Dialogues, see these Educator Resource Center articles:
Create and Publish Dialogue Items (ERC)
Effectively Using Dialogue Items (ERC)
AI Grading in Assignments and Peer Reviews
Purpose: Immediate, rigorous grading of open-ended submissions with personalized feedback
Where available: Assignment items, Peer Review assignments
Supported prompts and file types: Rich text and file uploads (video, audio, image, code)
WWHAA integration: Apply (hands-on practice), Assess (summative skill validation)
ASSIGNMENT Items with AI Grading
AI-graded questions use our AI grading system to evaluate text responses and file uploads (e.g., video, audio, code), providing a grade based on the rubrics you set up plus immediate, actionable feedback to help learners review concepts and assess their understanding.

Use cases:
Activities that involve artifact submissions or reflective responses
Quiz questions that require open-ended responses

Once you’ve developed the step-by-step instructions and submission prompts for an activity, create an Assignment item with your AI-graded questions and generate the rubrics for each submission prompt using the on-platform rubric generator tool. Review and revise the rubrics as needed before publishing. 

For more information, see this Educator Resource Center article:
Add AI-Graded Questions to Assignments (ERC)
PEER REVIEW Items with AI Grading
Note: As a first option, please use AI-graded assignments, reserving peer review assignments for justifiable use cases with well-designed rubrics. 

In peer review assignments, learners review and grade each other’s work. These are best used for assignments that do not have a single correct answer and require human evaluation, such as essays, design projects, case studies, etc. Peer review assignments facilitate this type of human evaluation at scale. 

The key to an effective peer review assignment is a well-structured rubric. Ask learners to rate individual components of the submission separately. Use simple, concrete language and quantified standards whenever possible.

Design the assignment with clear instructions and details on what learners need to submit. We recommend providing examples of the type of work you’re expecting to see and share the rubric with learners so they know how they will be evaluated (and how they will evaluate others). 

When AI grading is enabled for a peer review assignment, submissions are graded by our AI-grading system, providing a grade based on the rubrics you set up plus immediate, actionable feedback to help learners review concepts and assess their understanding. 

Learners also grade each others’ submissions. So peer review assignments work best when learners receive value in grading and critiquing each other’s work. If assessment of the learning objectives is the main priority (rather than facilitating peer-to-peer sharing of ideas), use a regular Assignment item with AI-grading instead of a Peer Review assignment.

For more information, see this Educator Resource Center article:
AI Grading in Peer Review Assignments

When designing your first peer review assignment, start with the design template below. Once you’ve mastered the basics; then consider using the import template for authoring the rubric. 

Design template (Google Docs): Peer Review Template | Peer Review Example
