Access the Brand Foundation Resources Folder for materials and guidelines needed to produce on-brand video content. The folder includes:

Slide Deck
What It Is: Guidelines for voice/tone, wardrobe, set design, remote shooting, lower-thirds, design files, B-roll usage, and video intros/outros.
How to Use It: Reference the slide deck for detailed instructions and best practices during video production.

B-roll Folder
What It Is: Curated approved footage for vignette videos demonstrating desired quality and style.
How to Use It: Select footage for visual consistency and use as reference for future B-roll production standards.

Photography Folder
What It Is: Approved stock photos for platform use; e.g., XDP, readings, assignments.
How to Use It: Use when custom images aren't provided by the branding team.

Additional Stock Footage and Photography Sources
Pexels, Pixabay, Freepik, Unsplash
Explore these platforms for free, licensed images and videos that align with the brand identity.
Use Pexels for open-source images and Pixabay, Freepik, and Unsplash for high-quality stock photos.
Ensure proper licensing and attribution, if required, before using external assets.
Video Scripts
General Video Guidelines
Keep all videos under 7 minutes in length
Start with a hook to draw in the learner
Speak directly to learners ("you") and keep it conversational
Avoid using jargon and define specialized terms or acronyms
Ensure metaphors and analogies translate cross-culturally
Illustrate concepts with real-world applications or examples
Create each video to stand alone; do not refer to "previous" or "next" videos
Use reminders like "as a quick recap" instead of cross-references
Provide clear, concise titles that reflect content without course-specific references
“Why” Vignette Videos
Length: 1-3 minutes
Answer: Why should the learner care about this topic or skill?
Start with a hook
Feature real experiences from industry, empathy, advice
Help learners see themselves in the story

EXAMPLE: Why Storytelling Matters on TikTok

The difference between content that goes viral and content that gets scrolled past? It's all in the story. That’s why mastering storytelling is essential for TikTok success.

People often make the mistake of thinking TikTok is just about dancing or trends, but at its core, TikTok is a storytelling platform. The most successful creators understand one critical fact: you have just 3 seconds to hook your viewer before they scroll away. Those first moments determine everything.

I learned this the hard way when I first started creating content. I spent hours filming high-quality videos with beautiful visuals, only to see them get barely any views. Why? Because I buried the hook too deep in the video. By the time I got to the interesting part, my audience was long gone.

TikTok's algorithm rewards watch time and engagement. When viewers watch your entire video and interact with it, the platform shows it to more people. This is why storytelling matters so much. It's the difference between 100 views and 100,000 views.

Consider a business account that sells handmade jewelry. Instead of just showing product photos, they might start their videos with: "The ring that made a customer cry with joy." That's a story hook that makes you want to know more.

Or consider a cooking account that begins with: "The 3-ingredient pasta that saved my dinner party when a guest announced they were gluten-free." Again, it's a story that pulls you in.

What successful creators understand is that TikTok isn't just a platform. It's a community built around shared stories. Whether your videos are 15 seconds or 10 minutes long, whether you're using video or the newer image carousel format, the principles of good storytelling remain the same: hook fast, create tension, and deliver satisfaction.

In today's crowded TikTok space, storytelling isn't just a bonus; it's absolutely essential. It's how you break through the noise, build a dedicated following, and transform casual viewers into loyal customers or engaged community members. By mastering these techniques, you'll be able to create content that not only stops the scroll but also forges genuine, lasting connections with your audience.

“Why” Vignette Videos – Level 1 Content Specifications
1. Purpose and Role in WWHAA
“Why” vignette videos support the Why phase of the WWHAA design footprint. They are short, motivating videos that answer one core question:
Why should the learner care about this topic or skill?
These vignettes:
Introduce a single skill, topic, or learning objective.
Create emotional and practical buy-in before learners encounter “What,” “How,” “Apply,” and “Assess” items.
Help learners see themselves and their goals in the story being told.
All “Why” vignettes must comply with the specifications below in addition to all other Level 1 requirements (Skill-First, Standalone & Stackable, WWHAA, accessibility, etc.).
2. Definition and Scope
A “Why” vignette is a short, instructor- or SME-led video with the following characteristics:
Duration: approximately 1–3 minutes.
Script length: approximately 200–450 words.
Character target: approximately 1,200–2,700 characters (including spaces), assuming ~6 characters per word.
Focus: motivation and relevance, not detailed instruction.
Connection: directly linked to the lesson’s or module’s learning objective(s).
“What” readings and “How” screencasts explain what something is and how to do it. “Why” vignettes explain why it’s worth learning and using.
“Why” vignettes are not:
Full instructional lectures.
Tutorials or walkthroughs.
Generic welcome videos unrelated to a specific skill or learning outcome.
3. Length and Duration Requirements
To maintain focus and impact:
Video duration:
Minimum: 1 minute
Maximum: 3 minutes
Script length:
Recommended: ~200–450 words total.
Character target: ~1,200–2,700 characters (including spaces) for the full vignette script.
This typically breaks down into:
Hook: 1–2 sentences.
Body: ~250–400 words.
Character target for body section: ~1,500–2,400 characters (including spaces).
Wrap-up: 1–2 short lines.
If a script exceeds 450 words:
Authors should tighten language and remove repetition.
The vignette should not be split into multiple parts; the purpose is a single, focused motivational moment.
4. Narrative Structure and Content Requirements
Every “Why” vignette must follow a clear, three-part narrative structure:
4.1 Hook (Opening, 1–2 Sentences)
Purpose:
Quickly grab attention and make the relevance obvious.
Requirements:
1–2 concise sentences.
Use language at or below 5th-grade reading level for the hook.
Clearly signal why this matters in the simplest possible terms.
Address the learner directly as “you” where natural.
Examples of hook intentions (not exact wording requirements):
“You use data every day—even if you don’t think of yourself as a ‘data person.’”
“If you can automate a task that takes you an hour every week, you get that hour back for the rest of your career.”
4.2 Body (Main Section, ~250–400 Words)
Purpose:
Build the case for why the skill or topic is important, valuable, and worth the learner’s time and effort.
Required content emphasis:
Job relevance:
How the skill or tool shows up in real job tasks.
How it helps learners do their work more effectively or advance in their careers.
Real-world preparation:
How the skill relates to realistic challenges or scenarios learners are likely to encounter.
Industry significance:
Why the skill/tool matters in the broader industry or field.
Value proposition:
What makes this skill worth learning now (e.g., opportunity, efficiency, impact).
Recommended strengthening elements (at least one should be present; several may be combined):
End results:
Describe the impact this skill or tool has on the job or in solving a concrete problem.
Authority via storytelling:
Brief, authentic anecdotes or experiences from the SME’s or industry’s real practice.
Empathy:
Acknowledge that learning can be challenging; share “I’ve been there too” moments.
Advice:
Offer reflective guidance such as “Here’s what I would have done differently earlier in my career.”
Direct address (“you”):
Help learners imagine themselves using the skill: “You’ll be able to…”.
Constraints:
The body should stay focused on “why,” not “how.”
Avoid detailed technical steps, interface descriptions, or code walk-throughs.
4.3 Wrap-Up (Closing, 1–2 Lines)
Purpose:
Reinforce the core takeaway and invite learners to continue into the lesson.
Requirements:
1–2 short sentences.
Summarize why the skill matters.
Gently encourage continued learning or practice (e.g., “In this lesson, you’ll start building that skill step by step.”).
Avoid promises that cannot be guaranteed (e.g., guaranteed jobs or salaries).
5. Content Integrity and Factual Accuracy
“Why” vignettes must be truthful, non-exaggerated, and evidence-respecting.
Authors must not:
Invent or exaggerate statistics, facts, or case studies.
Attribute quotes to real people without verifiable sources.
Use vague or generic success stories that cannot be substantiated.
When referring to:
Trends (e.g., demand for a skill).
Impact (e.g., productivity improvements).
Outcomes (e.g., career opportunities).
Authors should:
Keep statements general and accurate (“This skill is widely used in data analysis roles”) unless specific, verifiable evidence is available.
Avoid precise claims (“This skill will double your salary”) unless supported by reliable data and aligned to broader content standards.
If more detailed data or specific claims are used, they should be:
Aligned with the factual accuracy expectations described elsewhere in the Level 1 spec.
Based on reputable sources and internally reviewed where appropriate.
6. Coursera Brand Voice (Who We Are)
All “Why” vignettes must embody the Coursera brand voice. Authors should deliberately check their scripts against these four attributes:
Magnetic
Use active voice and confident, straightforward statements.
Spark curiosity about what the learner will be able to do.
Keep the pacing energetic and focused.
Emphasize the opportunity that comes from learning the skill.
Uplifting
Proceed from a positive, encouraging stance.
Connect small steps (this lesson) to big goals (career advancement, new possibilities).
Emphasize what learners can do and how they can grow.
Focus on beneficial outcomes, not fear or scarcity.
Trusted
Be accurate and thoughtful; do not over-promise.
Avoid jargon and ambiguity; explain ideas plainly.
Be inclusive in examples and scenarios.
Maintain a consistent, professional tone throughout.
Inventive
Where relevant, highlight:
Partnerships, collaborations, or innovations (without turning the vignette into marketing).
Major shifts or innovations in the field the learner should know about.
Show learners how the field is changing and how learning this skill positions them for the future.
7. Coursera Brand Tone (How We Communicate)
Tone is how the script sounds to learners. It should adapt to context while remaining true to Coursera’s personality.
Clear and Confident
Directly answer the learner’s core questions:
“What is this about?”
“Why should I care?”
Show how taking action (starting the lesson, practicing the skill) leads to new opportunities.
Connect the message to concrete outcomes (e.g., solving a specific type of problem at work).
Conversational
Use natural, human language.
Be concise; avoid overly complex sentences and filler.
Sound like a supportive expert speaking directly to the learner.
Empathetic and Motivating
Acknowledge that learning something new can feel challenging.
Avoid:
Negative or shaming language (“If you don’t know this, you’re behind.”).
Colloquialisms, idioms, or expressions that may not translate well globally.
Words or phrases with offensive or problematic origins.
Encourage learners and make them feel capable of progressing.
8. Language and Accessibility Requirements
To support a global and diverse learner base:
Reading level:
The opening hook must be written at or below a 5th-grade reading level.
The remainder of the script should aim for clear, accessible language suitable for a broad, international audience.
Clarity:
Avoid unexplained acronyms or specialized jargon.
When a technical term is necessary, provide a simple, high-level explanation.
Inclusivity:
Use diverse, inclusive examples and scenarios.
Avoid stereotypes about roles, regions, or backgrounds.
9. Style Do’s and Don’ts
9.1 Do
Do:
Use “you” to speak directly to learners.
Ground motivation in real tasks, problems, and roles.
Use brief, vivid anecdotes from realistic industry experience.
Show empathy (“I’ve been there too”) when appropriate.
Offer meaningful, concise advice (“Here’s what I wish I’d known sooner.”).
9.2 Don’t
Do not:
Invent or exaggerate stats, quotes, or outcomes.
Use generic, unverifiable success stories.
Rely on hype or fear (“If you don’t learn this, you’ll be left behind.”).
Use phrases like “let’s dive in,” “deep dive,” or similar overused metaphors in the script.
Overcomplicate the message; the vignette should simplify and humanize the “why,” not add cognitive load.
10. Authoring Process and Checklist
Authors (or vendor partners) creating “Why” vignettes should follow this process:
Clarify the Learning Objective
Identify the specific skill or topic this vignette introduces.
Write down one clear sentence that completes:
“After this lesson, learners will be able to…”
Collect Context
Review the associated:
“What” reading(s).
“How” demonstration(s).
“Apply” and “Assess” activities.
Determine how the vignette can bridge learners from their current state to caring about this upcoming content.
Draft the Hook
Write 1–2 short sentences explaining why this matters in the simplest terms possible.
Confirm hook reads at or below 5th-grade level and uses “you” where natural.
Build the Body
Connect the skill to:
Job tasks or real-world activities.
Industry or field importance.
Outcomes learners care about (e.g., efficiency, creativity, impact).
Incorporate at least one of:
End-result framing.
Brief, authentic anecdote.
Empathetic reflection.
Actionable advice.
Keep the total script within ~200–450 words.
Write the Wrap-Up
Summarize the main “why” in 1–2 lines.
Invite learners forward:
“In the next items, you’ll start putting this into practice.”
Review for Voice, Tone, and Accuracy
Check against Sections 5–9 for brand alignment.
Remove any unverified facts or implied guarantees.
Simplify sentences for clarity and global accessibility.
Final Self-Check
 Duration target (1–3 minutes) and length (~200–450 words) are reasonable.
 The vignette clearly answers: “Why should the learner care?”
 Hook is short, simple, and learner-facing.
 Body focuses on motivation and real-world relevance, not step-by-step instruction.
 Wrap-up reinforces the takeaway and encourages continued learning.
 Script is standalone and makes sense even if reused in another course/program context.

“How” Screencast Videos – Level 1 Content Specifications
1. Purpose and Role in WWHAA
“How” screencast videos support the How phase of the WWHAA design footprint. They focus on procedural knowledge—showing learners how to do something in a concrete tool, environment, or workflow.
These screencasts:
Demonstrate step-by-step processes learners need to perform.
Bridge the gap between conceptual understanding (“What”) and hands-on practice (“Apply”).
Model good practices and techniques in authentic tools and interfaces.
All “How” screencasts must comply with the specifications below in addition to all other Level 1 requirements (Skill-First, Standalone & Stackable, WWHAA, accessibility, etc.).
2. Definition and Screencast Types
A “How” screencast is a screen-capture-based instructional video (no on-camera presenter) that demonstrates a workflow, process, or technique in a specific tool or environment.
There are two supported types of “How” screencasts:
2.1 Demonstration Tutorial
Purpose:
Show learners what to do while they watch, without expecting them to perform actions simultaneously.
Pacing:
Smooth, continuous flow; minimal deliberate pauses for learner activity.
Language:
“I’ll show you how to…” style, describing actions the instructor performs on screen.
Typical duration:
~3–5 minutes.
Focus:
Clarity and completeness of the demonstration; learners can later replicate steps in their own time.
2.2 Follow-Along Tutorial
Purpose:
Guide learners to perform tasks as they watch, step by step.
Pacing:
Deliberate, with clear transitions and explicit pause points for learners to complete actions.
Language:
“Now you’ll…” or “Now you…” style, with direct instructions and prompts.
Typical duration:
~5–7 minutes for the same content that would fit into a shorter demonstration.
Focus:
Detailed, step-by-step guidance with explicit practice intervals built into the video.
Each “How” screencast must be clearly designed as either:
a Demonstration Tutorial, or
a Follow-Along Tutorial,
and must follow the requirements associated with that type.
3. Length, Scope, and Splitting Content
3.1 Script Length
Typical script length (spoken narration only):
Minimum: ~300 words
Maximum: ~900 words
Character range for narration (including spaces): ~1,800–5,400 characters.
As a guideline:
Demonstration tutorials usually fall around 300–600 words.
Follow-along tutorials usually fall around 400–900 words, due to additional instructions and pause cues.
Character guidance by type:
Demonstration tutorials: ~1,800–3,600 characters.
Follow-along tutorials: ~2,400–5,400 characters.
3.2 Video Duration
Demonstration: ~3–5 minutes.
Follow-along: ~5–7 minutes.
3.3 Scope and Splitting
If the process or workflow is too extensive for a single 3–7 minute screencast:
Authors should split the content into multiple screencasts, typically 2–5 minutes each.
Each screencast should:
Have a clear, focused goal (e.g., “Connecting to the data source,” “Configuring basic settings,” “Publishing the report”).
Include its own short hook and wrap-up, even if part of a mini-series.
When planning, outline the workflow and identify natural breakpoints where a learner’s sense of completion or milestone is clear.
4. Critical Accessibility Requirements
“How” screencasts must be fully usable for learners who are relying on audio, captions, and assistive technologies. This requires explicit narration of all on-screen actions.
4.1 Verbalization of On-Screen Actions
For every screencast:
Every on-screen action must be verbalized in the spoken script, including:
Cursor movements that matter to the task (e.g., “I’m moving to the Home tab in the ribbon.”).
All clicks and selections (e.g., “I’ll click the ‘Run’ button in the top-right corner.”).
Typing actions (e.g., “Now I’m typing SELECT * FROM sales into the query editor.”).
Visual changes that affect understanding (e.g., “A new panel appears on the right showing our filter options.”).
No action should appear in the planned visual sequence (screen recording) without a corresponding description in the spoken script.
This ensures that learners who cannot see the screen can still follow the logic and structure of the task.
4.2 Verbalization of Pause Points (Follow-Along Tutorials)
For follow-along tutorials, every planned pause for learner action must be clearly verbalized, including:
When to pause:
“Pause the video now…”
What to do:
“…and create a new worksheet named ‘Summary’.”
How they’ll know they’ve completed the task correctly:
“You’ll know you’re ready to continue when you see the ‘Summary’ sheet listed alongside your other tabs.”
When to resume:
“When you’re done, resume the video to continue.”
Pause points should be used:
For extended actions that take more than a few seconds.
For practice segments where learners apply the skill in their own context (e.g., in their own document, dataset, or environment).
Quick actions that take 1–2 seconds (e.g., a single button click) typically do not require a formal pause directive, as learners can follow along in real time.
5. Script and Content Structure
All “How” screencasts must follow a clear three-part structure: Hook, Body, and Wrap-up.
5.1 Hook (1–2 Sentences)
Opening phrase requirement:
Always begin the spoken script with “In this video…”
(Do not use “Today” as an opener.)
Purpose:
Briefly explain why this specific procedure or workflow matters.
Set expectations for what learners will be able to do by the end.
Characteristics:
1–2 short, punchy sentences.
Simple, accessible language (similar expectations as for “Why” vignettes, though not strictly under 5th-grade reading level overall).
Directly address the learner: “In this video, you’ll learn how to…”
5.2 Body (Step-by-Step Demonstration)
The body of the screencast should:
Present a logical, sequential set of steps.
For each step:
Explain what the step accomplishes and why it’s needed.
Describe exactly what appears on screen and what the instructor is doing (for demonstration types).
For follow-along:
Provide clear instructions for what the learner should do.
Use pause points for extended actions (see Section 4.2).
For Demonstration Tutorials:
Focus on:
Showing the full process with clear narration.
Maintaining a smooth pace without frequent pauses.
Suitable for:
Introducing a workflow that learners will revisit.
Complex or multi-stage tasks where learners first need an overview.
For Follow-Along Tutorials:
Focus on:
Guiding learners through the workflow as they do it.
Incorporating planned opportunities for practice.
Require:
More explicit instructions and cue phrases (“Now you’ll…”).
Clear guidance at each pause point.
5.3 Wrap-up (1–2 Lines)
Reinforce the key takeaway:
What the learner can now do.
How this connects to their broader goals or to the next course component.
Encourage continued learning:
“Next, you’ll use this setup in a hands-on assignment to analyze your own data.”
Keep it brief and focused on outcomes and next steps.
6. Step Design and Pause Point Guidance
6.1 Quick vs. Extended Actions
To avoid overwhelming learners:
Quick actions (1–2 seconds):
Example: clicking a tab, opening a menu, toggling a checkbox.
Learners can follow in real time if desired.
No formal “pause now” directive needed.
Extended actions (more than a few seconds):
Example: writing a paragraph of code, formatting multiple elements, configuring a complex dialog.
Should be paired with an explicit pause directive and clear instructions.
6.2 Follow-Along Tutorials: Practice Segments
In follow-along tutorials:
Use practice segments where learners apply the skill in their own context (e.g., their own project or document).
Each practice segment must:
Provide clear instructions on what to do.
Indicate how learners can verify success.
Remind learners to resume the video once ready.
7. Visual and Technical Requirements
“How” screencasts are screen-based: the instructor does not appear on camera. Visual clarity and accessibility are critical.
7.1 Screen Capture and Layout
Resolution:
1920×1080 (16:9 aspect ratio) is recommended for most screencasts.
Cursor:
Use a clearly visible cursor.
Clicks should be easy to see (e.g., subtle highlight or ripple), especially when interacting with small UI elements.
Text size and readability:
On-screen text (e.g., tool UI, labels, code, annotations) should be large enough to read on smaller devices:
Aim for a minimum of 16pt equivalent for body text in slides or overlays.
Avoid clutter; focus the learner’s view on relevant areas (use zoom when needed).
Zoom and focus:
Use zoom or tight cropping for small or dense UI components.
Avoid rapid camera moves or flashing changes.
7.2 Visual Accessibility
Color contrast:
Ensure a minimum color contrast ratio of 4.5:1 for text or important UI elements presented as part of instruction.
Use of color:
Do not rely on color alone to convey meaning (e.g., “click the red button”).
Supplement with shapes, labels, or annotations as needed.
Captions and transcripts:
All screencasts must support accurate captions and transcripts, aligned with the spoken script and including narration of visual changes.
7.3 Code Visualization (When Applicable)
When demonstrating code:
Use a monospaced font with adequate size and line spacing for readability.
Use syntax highlighting that:
Distinguishes key elements (functions, strings, keywords, comments).
Maintains adequate contrast and accessibility.
Consider showing:
Code and its output side-by-side where helpful (e.g., split screen).
Narration should:
Verbally identify and explain important parts of the code.
Clearly describe what is being typed or changed.
8. Coursera Brand Voice and Tone
“How” screencasts must reflect the same brand voice and tone as other course elements.
8.1 Voice (Who We Are)
Magnetic
Use active voice and confident language.
Foster curiosity by pointing out interesting results or patterns learners will see on screen.
Keep pacing dynamic but not rushed.
Uplifting
Emphasize learners’ progress as they complete steps.
Connect small technical wins to larger goals (e.g., “This may seem small, but it’s the foundation of a reliable pipeline.”).
Trusted
Provide accurate, precise instructions.
Avoid jargon where possible; explain necessary terms clearly.
Use realistic examples; do not exaggerate capabilities or outcomes.
Inventive
When appropriate, show innovative uses of tools or workflows.
Highlight partnerships or relevant research visually and verbally where it genuinely supports learning.
8.2 Tone (How We Communicate)
Clear and Confident
Answer core viewer questions:
“What am I doing?”
“Why am I doing it this way?”
Connect each step to a desired result or outcome.
Conversational
Use natural, supportive language (“You’ll notice…”, “If you make a mistake, you can…”).
Be concise and avoid unnecessary tangents.
Empathetic and Motivating
Acknowledge that learners might make errors or need to replay steps.
Avoid negative or shaming language.
Encourage learners (“If this feels unfamiliar now, that’s normal. With a few repetitions, these steps will start to feel natural.”).
9. What to Avoid
To maintain quality and consistency, authors of “How” screencasts must avoid:
Inventing or exaggerating facts, statistics, or examples about tools or outcomes.
Including unverified claims or generic, vague success stories.
Using overused phrases like “let’s dive in” or “deep dive” in introductions.
Overcomplicating the message with cluttered visuals or too many on-screen elements at once.
Rapid screen transitions without explanation or context.
Showing cursor movements or UI actions without narrating them.
Referring to an on-screen presenter (the instructor is not visible).
Starting with “Today…” instead of “In this video…”.
Designing follow-along tutorials that rush through steps without adequate time or clear pause instructions.
10. Authoring Process and Checklist
When designing a “How” screencast, authors should follow this process:
Define the Goal and Type
Identify the specific skill or task learners will complete by the end.
Decide whether the screencast is a Demonstration or Follow-Along tutorial.
Scope the Content
Outline the steps involved.
Confirm whether the workflow fits comfortably into a 3–7 minute video.
If not, plan to split into multiple shorter screencasts.
Draft the Script
Write a brief hook that begins with “In this video…” and states the goal in simple terms.
Script each step:
What is happening on screen.
What the narrator says.
Why the step matters.
Include explicit pause instructions for follow-along tutorials where needed.
Plan Visuals and Technical Requirements
Choose the tool/environment to show.
Identify areas that will require zooming or special highlighting.
Ensure fonts, colors, and layout meet accessibility and readability standards.
Review for Accessibility and Brand Alignment
Confirm that every on-screen action is verbalized.
Check that instructions are clear, inclusive, and non-jargon heavy.
Verify brand voice and tone (Magnetic, Uplifting, Trusted, Inventive).
Final Self-Check
 Screencast type (Demonstration or Follow-Along) is explicit and consistent.
 Length and scope are appropriate (3–7 minutes; ~300–900 words).
 Hook starts with “In this video…” and clearly states the skill/task.
 All important actions and visual changes are described in narration.
 Follow-along tutorials include clear pause instructions for extended actions.
 Visual and technical setup meets accessibility and readability requirements.
 Screencast is standalone and reusable in multiple course contexts.
“What” Instructional Videos
Although we’re moving away from reliance on traditional instructional videos in our design footprint, there may be places where didactic videos make sense, such as to introduce key ideas or explain concepts. Here’s a template for creating these types of instructional videos.

Hook
Aim for at least 3-5 sentences, or up to two paragraphs where appropriate. 
See “How to Write Engaging Opening Hooks” for best practices and generative AI prompts to help with hook development. 

Example
Think of traditional education as a conveyor belt, moving at a fixed pace regardless of individual needs. Some learners fall off, unable to keep up, while others are eager to race ahead. Now, imagine learning as a choose-your-own-adventure book, where learners turn the page when they’re ready. That's mastery learning on Coursera.
Introduction
Introduce the topic of the video and what will be learned.
When discussing what will be learned, you might highlight how you’ll go about teaching it or what case studies or tools might be used.
Keep it short, concise and engaging.
This is effectively an extension of the hook above and is often intermingled with the hook.

Example
In this video, we'll explore how Coursera's mastery learning approach offers a way to help every learner succeed. We’ll do this by explaining what mastery learning is and showing you how it’s built into Coursera learning experiences. 
Learning Objective(s)
Cover no more than 1-3 tightly connected objectives per video.
If you’re having trouble keeping a video below 7 minutes, focus on a single objective. 
Start each learning objective with a specific, measurable Bloom’s action verb. 

Example
By the end of this video, you will be able to: 
Explain how Coursera courses draw from mastery learning principles.
Apply mastery learning principles to course design and development. 
Body
Break down the topic into 2-4 key points or subtopics that support the video’s learning objective(s).
Organize the content in a clear, sequential manner that builds understanding step-by-step.
For each main point, offer concrete examples, case studies, or demonstrations to illustrate concepts.
Provide enough detail to thoroughly explain concepts, but avoid unnecessary tangents.
Include smooth transitions between main points to maintain flow and coherence.
Use rhetorical questions, analogies, or in-video questions to keep viewers interested and actively thinking.
Ensure each part of the body directly supports the video’s stated learning objective(s).

Example
[Key concept or point] The main point behind mastery learning is to master a topic before proceeding to the next topic. This model embraces failure as a form of feedback for learning. Rather than “punish” a learner for failing to understand something, the learner is given the opportunity to try again. [Illustration of concept with concrete examples] Here’s a visualization of how mastery learning can function on Coursera. …
Summary
Highlight key ideas or takeaways. 
Draw out the implications of the ideas taught.
Do not simply restate the learning objective(s).
Keep this short, concise and useful.

Example
In this video, we examined Coursera’s approach to mastery learning. Mastery learning:
Promotes a deeper understanding of the subject matter by ensuring learners master each concept before moving forward. 
Encourages a positive learning environment where failure is seen as a part of the learning process, not a setback. 
Provides personalized learning experiences by providing informative feedback based on individual performance on formative activities. 
Call to Action
Outline the next steps learners should take to apply what they’ve learned.
Start sentences with strong imperative verbs (“Start…”, “Try…”).
Keep this short, concise and powerful (one paragraph of 3-5 sentences).
Be relevant to the video content and learning goals.
Create a sense of urgency or excitement.
Be specific and actionable.
See “How to Write Effective Calls to Action” for best practices and generative AI prompts to help with hook development. 

Example
Now that you’ve learned about mastery learning, you’re ready to apply it to your course design. Start by developing a course outline with both formative and summative assessments. Then consider what kind of feedback learners may need on the formative assessments to successfully demonstrate mastery on the summative assessments.

