Coursera Best Practices for Creating Engaging and Effective Instructional Videos (ERC)
About the Different Styles of Instructional Videos and When to Use Them (ERC)
Tips and Examples for Creating Module Introductions and Welcome Videos (ERC)
Video Visuals
Minimize Text and Bullets
Remove repetitive slide titles (since these are unnecessary and simply add words)
Avoid nested sub-bullets (since this gets busy fast and indicates too much text)
Use a clean new slide for each new topic (since this helps cue the learner’s attention without overburdening them with a build-up prior text)

If a slide has more than 5-7 words on it, look for opportunities to condense it.
Learning objective slides will be longer (but don’t let text encroach on the lower fifth)  
Quotes that use (short) text blocks will be longer (but use sparingly) 
Using Text in Visuals
Text shown on screen should always be verbalized in the presentation. But everything in the verbal presentation does not need to be shown on screen. 
Focus on showing key words on screen (rather than sentences).
Don’t let the on-screen text mimic a teleprompter (it’s for the audience not the presenter).
Why Images Are Better Than Text
Images are always better than text. Why? We have two channels for processing information: linguistic and visual. The linguistic channel includes both written and spoken language, so presenting too much of both at the same time clogs up this channel, increasing the cognitive load. But we can process spoken words (linguistic channel) and visual images (visual channel) without that problem. This is why a good image/graphic that complements the verbal presentation is more effective than on-screen text. So, when using text, use selective text as if the text were images (something learners can “view” without needing to “read” per se). 
Visuals Best Practices
Use compelling visuals that complement the verbal explanation and support key concepts 
Minimize text/bullet points and maximize visual imagery
Limit text where you can
Introduce one bullet point at a time
Incorporate visual variety to keep learners engaged
Beware complex graphics; cue the learner to the portion of graphics where you want them to place their attention (e.g., magnification, highlighting)
Avoid putting vital content in the lower fifth of the screen so it won't interfere with subtitles
Keep slides in motion (don’t spend too much time on a single slide)
Follow WCAG guidelines for accessibility regarding color contrast, information display, etc.
