Guidelines for Using Text, Images, and Slides in Videos (ERC)
Coursera Best Practices for Creating Engaging and Effective Instructional Videos (ERC)
Video Production
Characteristics of Quality Videos
Instructor Presence. The instructor presents with energy and genuine interest in the subject matter. Their approach is conversational, ensuring the delivery is animated and engaging.

Lighting. Lighting is appropriate so that the instructor is well-lit. Three-point lighting is commonly used to achieve this, ensuring that the subject is visible without excessive shadows.

Audio Quality. A quality microphone is used. Audio background noise and echo is omitted to ensure clear speech. 

Intro/Outro. Include partner (or Coursera for Coursera-owned) bumpers with copyright information at the beginning and end of the first and last video of the course. During this time, music should play while the bumpers are on screen.

Transitions. Transitions between segments in the video must be seamless without causing abrupt or jarring changes in the visual experience.
Readings
Reading items typically consist of original work written specifically for the course, following these best practices:
Keep readings short, concise, and focused just like videos
Use headings and subheadings to visually chunk ideas into sections
Use visuals/graphics to help learners conceptualize complex concepts
Use screenshots to illustrate instructions for software applications
Refer to and fully explain charts, tables, and graphics in the text
Keep the language conversational and accessible
Address the learner directly (“you”)
Define technical terms and spell out acronyms
State the learning objective at the beginning
Summarize the key takeaways at the end
Provide alt text for all images and complex diagrams
Follow WCAG guidelines for accessibility
“What” Readings – Level 1 Content Specifications
1. Purpose and Role in WWHAA
“What” readings support the What phase of the WWHAA design footprint. They provide the core declarative knowledge learners need to understand what a skill is, why it matters, and how it connects to the module’s learning objectives.
These readings:
Focus on facts, concepts, terminology, and processes.
Lay the conceptual foundation for the hands-on work learners will do in the How, Apply, and Assess phases.
Are written to be standalone items that can be reused across courses and programs.
All “What” readings must comply with the specifications below in addition to all other Level 1 requirements (Skill-first, Standalone & Stackable, WWHAA, accessibility, etc.).
2. Definition and Scope
A “What” reading is a course item that:
Explains core concepts and definitions aligned to a specific Skill and its Skill Expressions.
Emphasizes declarative knowledge (what something is, how it works, what its components are).
Uses didactic exposition supported by examples, diagrams, and/or simple process descriptions.
Prepares learners for guided practice (How), independent application (Apply), and assessment (Assess).
“What” readings are not:
Step-by-step “click this button” walkthroughs (those belong in How/Apply).
Opinion pieces, thought leadership, or marketing content.
Primary assessment vehicles (though they may include simple reflection prompts).
3. Length Requirements
All “What” readings must meet the following word count constraints:
Required length:
Minimum: 800 words
Maximum: 1,500 words
Character range (including spaces): ~4,800–9,000 characters, using ~6 characters per word as the planning baseline.
The word count applies to the main reading content only (from title through Conclusion).
The KEY STATS AND SOURCES FOR REVIEWER’S USE section (see Section 7) is not included in this word count.
If a single reading would exceed 1,500 words, authors must:
Split the content into two or more readings, each adhering to the 800–1,500 word requirement.
Ensure each reading is coherent and standalone, with its own Introduction and Conclusion.
4. Structure and Formatting Requirements
All “What” readings must follow a consistent, predictable structure to support reuse and learner navigation.
4.1 Title and Heading Hierarchy
The reading title must:
Appear at the top of the item.
Use a level 1 heading (H1).
Follow the format:
TITLE: Your Title Here
Use the following heading hierarchy for the body:
H2 (##) for all main sections.
H3 (###) for subsections.
H4 (####) for further subdivisions if needed.
4.2 Required Section Structure
Each “What” reading must include at least the following structure:
Introduction (required, first main section)
Header: ## Introduction
Content:
A short, punchy hook (1–2 sentences) that connects to learner goals, real-world relevance, or a compelling question.
A brief introduction to the learning objectives, explaining what learners will understand by the end of the reading (in plain language).
Body Sections (one or more main sections, H2)
Each main section uses a descriptive H2 heading, not generic labels like “Body” or “Main Content”.
Authors should structure content into logical chunks that:
Introduce core concepts.
Explain key terms and relationships.
Provide examples and, where helpful, simple step-wise descriptions of processes.
Conclusion (required, final main section)
Header: ## Conclusion
Content:
A concise wrap-up of key takeaways.
A forward-looking note that connects the reading to:
Upcoming items in the module (e.g., hands-on activities, assessments) without relying on fragile cross-references.
Practical next steps learners can take (e.g., “In the upcoming activity, you’ll…” framed in a standalone-friendly way).
4.3 Template
Authors should use the following template as a baseline for all “What” readings (adapt wording as needed, but maintain structure):
# TITLE: [Title Goes Here]

## Introduction  
[Hook goes here in 1–2 sentences…]

[Learning objective introduction goes here: what the learner will understand or be able to explain after this reading…]

## [Main Heading 1]  
[Content that develops one major concept or cluster of related concepts…]

## [Main Heading 2]  
[Content that adds further concepts, examples, or perspectives…]

… (add additional main sections as needed, all H2) …

## Conclusion  
[Wrap up key ideas, highlight the most important takeaways, and connect briefly to how this understanding will support learners in practice or in upcoming course activities.]

---

# KEY STATS AND SOURCES FOR REVIEWER’S USE  
- [Stat or factual claim] – [Source name], [URL], [Publication date]
- [Stat or factual claim] – [Source name], [URL], [Publication date]
5. Style and Accessibility Requirements
All “What” readings must follow a consistent style that aligns with Coursera’s brand and supports accessibility for a global learner base.
5.1 Language and Readability
Address learners directly using “you”.
Use conversational, plain language while remaining professional.
Avoid or explain:
Jargon, idioms, and culture-specific references.
Domain-specific terminology that has not been defined.
Define all technical terms and acronyms on first use:
Spell out the full term followed by the acronym in parentheses, then use the acronym thereafter.
5.2 Structure and Lists
Use headings to chunk content into logical, scannable sections.
Use bulleted or numbered lists when:
Presenting multiple related points.
Outlining steps in a process.
Avoid extremely long paragraphs; break up dense text to support skimming and comprehension.
5.3 Accessibility
All content must comply with WCAG-aligned accessibility practices, including:
Clear heading structure as specified above.
Sufficient contrast and legible font sizes in any embedded images or screenshots.
Avoidance of conveying meaning by color alone.
Any non-text element (images, diagrams, charts) must include:
Alt text recommendations (see Section 6).
A textual explanation in the reading itself when the visual is essential to understanding.
6. Visual Elements (Images, Diagrams, Tables)
Visuals in “What” readings should be instructionally necessary, not decorative.
6.1 When to Use Visuals
Use visuals to:
Clarify complex relationships or systems.
Illustrate stepwise processes or workflows.
Provide a conceptual overview that is hard to convey solely in prose.
Do not add visuals purely to “dress up” the reading.
6.2 Alt Text and Descriptions
For every non-decorative image or diagram, authors must:
Provide alt text recommendations that:
Convey the essential instructional information.
Avoid redundancy with nearby text; instead, complement it.
Ensure that the main narrative text:
Explains the visual’s relevance and helps learners interpret it.
6.3 Tables
Tables must be:
Properly formatted with header rows and meaningful column labels.
Used primarily for:
Comparisons (e.g., feature vs feature).
Structured data that benefits from tabular layout.
Avoid using tables solely for visual layout or design.
7. Factual Accuracy, Stats, and Sources
“What” readings must be accurate, current where relevant, and verifiable.
7.1 Key Stats and Sources Section
Each “What” reading must include a section at the end titled:
# KEY STATS AND SOURCES FOR REVIEWER’S USE
This section:
Is intended for internal review and quality assurance, not as learner-facing content.
Must list:
Any statistics, quantitative claims, or critical factual statements used in the reading.
For each, provide:
A brief description of the claim.
The source name, URL, and publication date (or “n.d.” if no date is available).
Is not counted in the 800–1,500 word requirement for the reading itself.
7.2 Use of Sources
Prefer:
High-quality, reputable sources (research articles, official documentation, industry reports, government or NGO data).
Up-to-date information for any time-sensitive topics.
Avoid:
Unsupported claims, vague generalizations, or unverifiable anecdotes.
When referencing Coursera proprietary research, clearly label it as such in the KEY STATS AND SOURCES section.
8. Coursera Brand Voice (Who We Are)
All “What” readings must embody Coursera’s brand voice. Authors should check their drafts against the four characteristics below:
Magnetic
Use active voice and confident, straightforward statements.
Spark curiosity by connecting concepts to real-world problems and opportunities.
Show passion for learning and highlight the “why” behind concepts.
Uplifting
Proceed from a positive, empowering stance.
Connect small wins (understanding a concept) to bigger goals (career growth, new opportunities).
Emphasize what learners can do next, not what they lack.
Trusted
Be accurate and appropriately detailed, avoiding overclaiming.
Avoid jargon and ambiguity; clarify terms and assumptions.
Be inclusive:
Use examples that reflect diverse people, industries, and contexts.
Avoid stereotypes and biased framing.
Inventive
Where appropriate, highlight relevant:
Partnerships.
Innovations in the field.
Research findings (including Coursera research, if available).
Show how the domain is evolving and how learners can stay current.
9. Coursera Brand Tone (How We Communicate)
Tone should reflect our personality in context of the learner’s journey.
Clear and Confident
Answer core questions directly: What is this? Why does it matter? How does it work at a high level?
Connect content to concrete outcomes (skills, tasks, career relevance).
Avoid hedging language unless uncertainty is important to acknowledge.
Conversational
Use natural, human language:
Contractions are acceptable where appropriate.
Avoid overly formal or academic phrasing.
Be concise; remove unnecessary filler and repetition.
Empathetic and Motivating
Assume learners may be:
New to the topic.
Balancing other commitments.
Learning in a second or third language.
Avoid:
Negative or shaming language.
Colloquialisms, idioms, or terms with offensive or problematic origins.
10. Authoring Process and Submission Checklist
Authors (or vendor partners) creating “What” readings should follow this process:
Identify Core Learning Objectives
Confirm which Skill and Skill Expressions this reading supports.
Draft 1–3 clear, concise learning objectives for the reading (even if not shown verbatim).
Craft the Introduction
Write a 1–2 sentence hook that resonates with learner needs or a real-world scenario.
Add a brief overview of what learners will understand by the end.
Organize the Body
Break content into 2–4 main sections (H2) with descriptive headings.
Use H3/H4 sparingly for logical subtopics.
Ensure the total length (Intro + body + Conclusion) is 800–1,500 words.
Write the Conclusion
Summarize key takeaways in a concise, learner-friendly way.
Connect the concepts to how they’ll support upcoming practice or real-world application.
Add Visuals (Optional but Recommended When Helpful)
Include diagrams, images, or tables where they clearly aid understanding.
Provide alt text recommendations and explanatory narrative in the body.
Review for Brand Voice, Tone, and Accessibility
Check against Sections 5, 8, and 9.
Ensure technical terms are defined and examples are inclusive.
Document Sources
Add a # KEY STATS AND SOURCES FOR REVIEWER’S USE section after the main content.
List each key factual or statistical claim with source, URL, and date.
Confirm this section is maintained outside the main word count.
Final Self-Check Before Submission
 Title uses TITLE: and H1.
 Sections follow required hierarchy (## Introduction, body sections as H2, ## Conclusion).
 Word count (Introduction through Conclusion) is 800–1,500 words.
 Reading is standalone and understandable if reused in a different course/program context.
 KEY STATS AND SOURCES section is present, clear, and not counted in the word total.
Embedding Articles or Resources in Readings
You can also embed articles/resources into readings for download assuming you have the rights to do so while following these guidelines:
Any content that belongs to others requires legal permissions to use and distribute for profit
Ensure downloads are provided in a format that all learners can access (e.g., PDF)
Linking to Open-Access Articles or Resources in Readings
Readings may also include links to open-access articles/resources, following these guidelines: 
External content should be reserved for optional resources for further exploration and should not be part of the primary learning path (i.e., learners won’t be tested on them)
When linking to an external article, ensure it can be accessed by learners around the world without needing to cross through a paywall
Include a brief introduction to provide context for external links so learners know where the link is taking them and why (i.e., don’t simply include a hyperlink in an otherwise blank reading item)
Ensure external links are reputable, credible, and accurate, and represent content the partner would feel comfortable sharing with learners.
Ensure external links are up to date, keeping in mind that links to external websites may change or break
Avoid external content that contains ads or elements that distract from the main content you want learners to read
Always use links rather than iframes, unless you have permissions to embed the content
To aid screen readers, hyperlink specific titles for links instead of using the full URL
Avoid Use of the Resources Section
What is the Resources Section of a Course?
The Resources section in Coursera courses is designed for supplemental materials that learners can access from the course home. These materials are not part of the main learning path and are not required to complete the course. Examples might include:

A glossary of important terms
Study tips for success
Installation instructions for required software
Reference texts, formulas, or diagrams (e.g., a periodic table)

Learners access these materials from the Resources page of the course, and instructors can choose whether resources are visible there or only accessible via direct links.


Guidance for Course Development
✅ Do upload files directly into a learning item in the main course material.
❌ Don’t add or link to files in the Resources section.

To facilitate modularity when building new content, do not add files to the Resources section. Instead, always place files directly into a learning item within the main learning path (e.g., a reading, video, or assignment).

This ensures that:

All materials remain accessible to learners when content is reused in new courses or skills paths.
Files are tied to the appropriate point in the learner journey, rather than living outside the course structure.
Hyperlinks will not break if a course is cloned or retrofitted into a new program.

If you want to provide supplemental reference material, create a dedicated learning item (e.g., a reading) within the course itself (e.g., end of module). This keeps the materials organized within the learning path itself and ensures learners always have access, regardless of where the course is delivered.
Multiple Choice Quiz Questions
You can set up both practice and graded quizzes in an Assignment item. Tailor feedback for each answer option. The feedback provided on practice quizzes should differ from the feedback provided on graded quizzes, as described below. 
Practice Assignment (Quiz) Feedback
On practice quizzes, provide option-level feedback that explains why each choice is correct or incorrect and let learners know what the correct answer should be. Explaining why each choice is correct or incorrect on practice (formative) quizzes heads off misconceptions and reinforces the development of accurate mental models. Plus, we’ve found from our own research that adding meaningful practice leads to a larger percentage of learners progressing through the course, helping both with understanding and motivation. 


Graded Assignment (Quiz) Feedback
On graded quizzes, provide option-level feedback that refers learners to relevant review items (e.g., video titles or topics) rather than revealing the answers. Mastery learning requires learners to pass each graded quiz to complete the course. Learners may retake a graded quiz until they succeed. So, we want to provide feedback to guide their studying in between attempts. Pointing learners to appropriate review items will help them focus their studying before retaking the quiz.


Question Writing Tips
Avoid negative phrasings
Avoid ambiguous wordings
Make use of different question types (e.g., single correct, multiple correct)
Multiple choice options should be authentic and plausible
Draw from actual concepts learners have encountered
Repeat key terms from the question in the answers (rather than using demonstrative pronouns such as “this” or “that”) for clarity
Question Variations
Question variations are important on graded assignments (quizzes) to prevent learners from encountering the same questions on retakes. This approach elevates the rigor of assignments by ensuring learners genuinely understand the material instead of memorizing answers to specific questions.

For courses seeking American Council on Education (ACE) credit recommendation, each graded question must have three unique variations. For example, a graded assignment with 10 quiz questions would require a total of 30 questions (3 variation per question stem). 

Entry-level Professional Certificates undergoing ACE Credit Recommendation must meet these standards to ensure rigor and academic integrity on graded multiple-choice quizzes (but the requirements may be met after launch):

3 variations per question
Attempt rate = 3 attempts/day
Submissions per attempt = 1
Time limit = 5 minutes/question

Guidelines for Writing Effective Question Variations

Same Learning Objective, Unique Questions. Each variation should assess the same learning objective, using questions with a different approach, scenario, or data point, while maintaining the core focus.

Diverse Question Types. Use a mix of question types (e.g., multiple-choice single correct, multiple correct, true/false) to evaluate the same learning objective from different angles.

Beyond Rephrasing. Go beyond minor wording changes. Consider alternative ways to approach the learning objective, presenting it in a new context or requiring a different type of thinking.
